The [National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine) (NASEM), often referred to simply as the [National Academies](/National_academy), stands as a formidable [congressionally chartered](/Congressional_charter) entity, functioning as the collective scientific [national academy](/National_academy) for the [United States of America](/United_States_of_America). This designation isn't as straightforward as it might seem, as the name "National Academies" is employed in a dual capacity. Firstly, it acts as an overarching, umbrella term, signifying the parent organization for its three distinct, yet interconnected, sub-divisions. These subdivisions operate with a degree of quasi-independence as honorific [learned society](/Learned_society) member organizations: the venerable [National Academy of Sciences](/National_Academy_of_Sciences) (NAS), the [National Academy of Engineering](/National_Academy_of_Engineering) (NAE), and the [National Academy of Medicine](/National_Academy_of_Medicine) (NAM). Secondly, the moniker serves as a distinct brand, specifically for the extensive array of studies and reports meticulously produced by the unified operating arm of these three academies. This operational division was originally known as the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council) (NRC).

Beyond their role as a collective intellectual powerhouse, the [National Academies](/National_academy) also fulfill crucial functions as [public policy](/Public_policy) advisors, diligently operating as [research institutes](/Research_institute), influential [think tanks](/Think_tank), and even specialized [public administration](/Public_administration) [consultants](/Consultant). Their expertise is brought to bear on issues of significant public importance, often at the direct request of the [federal government](/Federal_government_of_the_United_States). [5](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-5) [6](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-6) [7](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-7) [8](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering_and_Medicine#cite_note-8) [9](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-9)

Historically, the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council), the [National Academy of Engineering](/National_Academy_of_Engineering), and the [National Academy of Medicine](/National_Academy_of_Medicine) initially existed as activities or extensions of the more senior [National Academy of Sciences](/National_Academy_of_Sciences). This structure persisted until a significant reorganization transpired in 2015. At that point, they were formally reconfigured into distinct units within the newly unified [National Academies](/National_academy) framework. Crucially, this restructuring ensured the preservation of the original [National Academy of Sciences](/National_Academy_of_Sciences)'s foundational [charter status](/Congressional_charter) and corporate successorship.

Now operating under the joint governance of all three academies, the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council) is a prolific entity, responsible for generating approximately 200 publications on an annual basis. These reports are subsequently disseminated and made accessible by the [National Academies Press](/National_Academies_Press). The output of these reports is widely recognized and has been characterized as accurately reflecting the prevailing [scientific consensus](/Scientific_consensus) on a given subject. [10](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-10) *A consensus, of course, is merely the current agreement among a specific group. It's not a timeless truth, just what everyone can stomach for now.*

### History

The genesis of the [US National Academy of Sciences](/National_Academy_of_Sciences) can be traced back to an Act of Incorporation, a legislative decree dated March 3, 1863. This pivotal document was signed into law by none other than the then-[President of the United States](/President_of_the_United_States), [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln). [11](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-11) The Act laid down a clear mandate, stating unequivocally that "... the Academy shall, whenever called upon by any department of the Government, investigate, examine, experiment, and report upon any subject of science or art. ... " [11](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-11) One might imagine, with the nation embroiled in the brutal conflict of the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War), that the fledgling academy would be inundated with monumental scientific challenges. However, the initial problems presented to this new body were, shall we say, rather prosaic. Its early endeavors included addressing matters of "... coinage, weights and measures, iron ship hulls, and the purity of whiskey ..." [11](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-11) *Because, naturally, the integrity of a nation's spirits is just as crucial as its war effort. Priorities, I suppose.*

All organizations subsequently affiliated with this foundational body have been established under the same overarching [congressional charter](/Congressional_charter). This includes the two younger, yet equally distinguished, academies: the [National Academy of Engineering](/National_Academy_of_Engineering) (NAE), which came into existence in 1964, and the [National Academy of Medicine](/National_Academy_of_Medicine) (NAM). The latter was initially conceived as the Institute of Medicine in 1970 before being rechartered and renamed as the NAM in 2015. [12](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-12)

It was also under this very same enduring charter that the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council) was formally established in 1916. On June 19 of that year, the then-[US President Woodrow Wilson](/Woodrow_Wilson) made a direct request to the [National Academy of Sciences](/National_Academy_of_Sciences) to organize what he termed a "National Research Council." The fundamental purpose of this council, which was initially envisioned as the National Research Foundation, was multifaceted. It aimed, in part, to actively foster and encourage "the increased use of scientific research in the development of American industries ... the employment of scientific methods in strengthening the national defense ... and such other applications of science as will promote the national security and welfare." [13](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-13) *A classic move: when conflict looms, suddenly science becomes indispensable. Funny how that works.*

During that critical period, as the academy geared up to support national defense readiness, a specific initiative, the Committee on [Nitric Acid](/Nitric_acid) Supply, received the explicit approval of Secretary of War [Newton D. Baker](/Newton_D._Baker). [Nitric acid](/Nitric_acid) was not merely a chemical compound; it was a substance of paramount importance, forming the basic ingredient in the manufacture of propellants such as [cordite](/Cordite), high explosives, various dyes, essential [fertilizers](/Fertilizer), and a host of other critical products. However, its availability was severely constrained, a direct consequence of the engulfing global conflict of [World War I](/World_War_I). The [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council), acting through its dedicated committee, put forth a series of recommendations: the urgent importation of Chilean [saltpeter](/Potassium_nitrate) and the immediate construction of four new ordnance plants. These vital recommendations were officially accepted by the [War Department](/War_Department_(US)) in June 1917, though, as is often the case with grand plans, the plants were not brought to completion before the cessation of hostilities. [13](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-13)

In 1918, President Wilson further solidified the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council)'s existence, formalizing its role under [Executive Order](/List_of_United_States_federal_executive_orders) 2859. [14](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-14) [15](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-15) [16](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-16) Wilson's executive order meticulously outlined the general function of the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council) as follows:

"(T)o stimulate research in the mathematical. physical, and biological sciences. and in the application of these sciences to engineering, agriculture. medicine. and other useful arts. with the object of increasing knowledge, of strengthening the national defense, and of contributing in other ways to the public welfare." [11](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-11) *A rather sweeping mandate, don't you think? As if "public welfare" is some easily defined, universally agreed-upon concept. It's not.*

During the tumultuous years of [World War I](/World_War_I), when the [United States](/United_States_of_America) found itself actively engaged in warfare, the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council) assumed a dual operational identity. It functioned as both the Department of Science and Research of the [Council of National Defense](/Council_of_National_Defense) and concurrently as the Science and Research Division of the [United States Army Signal Corps](/United_States_Army_Signal_Corps). [17](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-17) Immediately upon the declaration of war, the council swiftly organized specialized committees, focusing their efforts on critical areas such as [anti-submarine warfare](/Antisubmarine_warfare) and [gas warfare](/Gas_warfare). [11](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-11)

On June 1, 1917, the council orchestrated a crucial meeting, bringing together scientific representatives from the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) and [France](/France) with interested parties from the [U.S.](/United_States_of_America) The subject of this high-stakes discussion was the pressing issue of submarine detection. [18](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-18) [19](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-19) A subsequent, equally significant meeting with the British and French delegations took place in [Paris](/Paris) in October 1918, where more intricate details of their ongoing work were finally disclosed. As a direct consequence of these collaborative discussions, the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council) advocated for the concerted effort of scientists to tackle the complex problems associated with submarine detection. The remarkable success of council-directed research in developing a functional [sound-based method](/Sonar) for identifying and tracking [submarines](/Submarine), alongside other vital military innovations, ensured the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council)'s continued existence even after the war concluded. However, it was gradually and deliberately decoupled from its direct military affiliations.

The Articles of Organization governing the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council) have, perhaps surprisingly, undergone remarkably few alterations throughout its long history. They have been modified on only three distinct occasions: in 1956, in January 1993, and most recently in July 2015. [20](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-20) *Proof that once a bureaucracy is established, it tends to stick around, regardless of minor adjustments.*

### The Academies

Main articles: [National Academy of Sciences](/National_Academy_of_Sciences), [National Academy of Engineering](/National_Academy_of_Engineering), and [National Academy of Medicine](/National_Academy_of_Medicine)

The [National Academy of Sciences](/National_Academy_of_Sciences), the [National Academy of Engineering](/National_Academy_of_Engineering), and the [National Academy of Medicine](/National_Academy_of_Medicine) function as distinct, yet interconnected, honorary membership organizations. Each of these prestigious bodies maintains its own independent governing Council and possesses the autonomous authority to elect its own new members annually. The combined membership across these three academies constitutes an impressive roster of over 6,300 distinguished scientists, engineers, and health professionals. The process for selecting new members for each organization is rigorous: candidates are elected annually by the existing members, a decision predicated solely on their demonstrated and continuing achievements in original research. By the very terms of the foundational 1863 [Congressional charter](/Congressional_charter), these three academies are bound to serve *[pro bono](/Pro_bono)* as "advisers to the nation on [science](/Science), [engineering](/Engineering), and [medicine](/Medicine)." *Because the greatest wisdom, apparently, is freely given. Or at least, officially.*

### Program units

The program units, which were previously known collectively as the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council), effectively constitute the operational arm of the three academies. Their primary mandate is to provide objective policy advice, a function critical to informing national discourse and decision-making. Despite having a separate historical charter (as noted above), this operating arm legally falls under the overarching charter of the [National Academy of Sciences](/National_Academy_of_Sciences). Consequently, the ultimate fiduciary responsibility rests with the NAS Council. However, in practical application, the NAS Council delegates much of its governing authority to a dedicated Governing Board of the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council). This board is notably chaired jointly by the presidents of all three academies, with additional members either chosen by these presidents or specifically designated within the individual charters of the respective academies.

Operating under this unique three-academy umbrella, the program units are responsible for generating a substantial volume of reports. These publications are intended to be influential, designed to shape policies, inform public opinion, and ultimately advance the pursuit of [science](/Science), [engineering](/Engineering), and [medicine](/Medicine) across the nation. [21](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-21) *One can only hope they actually achieve that lofty goal, rather than just adding to the pile of well-intentioned but ignored documents.*

The operational structure is further delineated into seven major divisions, each with its own specialized focus: the Division of Behavioral and Social Sciences and Education, the Division of Earth and Life Studies, the [Division of Engineering and Physical Sciences](/Engineering_and_Physical_Sciences), the Health and Medicine Division, the Policy and Global Affairs Division, the [Transportation Research Board](/Transportation_Research_Board), and the Gulf Research Program. [22](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-22)

