### Study process

The [National Academies](/National_academy) are driven by a fundamental objective: to meticulously obtain authoritative, objective, and scientifically balanced answers to some of the most difficult and pressing questions confronting the nation. [29](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-29) *A noble goal, if somewhat naive about the nature of "objective" answers in a world brimming with biases.* To achieve this, they enlist a vast network of top scientists, engineers, health professionals, and other experts, a pool not limited exclusively to those already holding membership within the academies. These individuals are brought together to diligently address the scientific and technical dimensions of society's myriad problems. Crucially, these experts serve as volunteers, generously contributing their time and intellect on study committees specifically convened to answer predefined sets of questions. All committee members, without exception, serve without monetary compensation.

It is important to clarify that NASEM itself does not engage in original research. Rather, its core function is to provide independent advice, synthesizing existing knowledge and data to inform policy. The primary financial sponsors of the Academies' work are federal agencies, though additional studies also receive funding from state agencies, various foundations, other private sponsors, and the National Academies' own endowment. A critical safeguard embedded in their process is that the external sponsors, regardless of their financial contribution, retain absolutely no control over the conduct or the ultimate results of a study, once the statement of task and budget have been formally finalized. Study committees gather extensive information from a multitude of sources, often through public meetings to ensure transparency. However, their critical deliberations occur in private, a deliberate measure designed to insulate the process from political pressures, the influence of special interest groups, and even the sway of the sponsors themselves.

Every report generated by the [National Academies](/National_academy) undergoes an exhaustive external review process. This is meticulously facilitated by an internal Report Review Committee, which is itself composed of esteemed members drawn from the NAS, NAE, and NAM. [30](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-30)

Through this rigorous study process, the [National Academies](/National_academy) consistently produce approximately 200 reports each year. These recent publications have tackled an astonishingly diverse range of subjects, including the pervasive [obesity epidemic](/Obesity_epidemic), the complex use of forensics in courtroom settings, the ecological threat posed by [invasive plants](/Invasive_plants), the alarming phenomenon of pollinator collapse, the persistent issue of [underage drinking](/Underage_drinking), the groundbreaking achievements of the [Hubble Space Telescope](/Hubble_Space_Telescope), the crucial topic of [vaccine safety](/Vaccine_safety), the speculative promise of the [hydrogen economy](/Hydrogen_economy), vital considerations for transportation safety, the undeniable reality of [climate change](/Global_warming), and the ever-present concerns of [homeland security](/Homeland_security). Many of these reports wield significant influence, directly shaping policy decisions. Others prove instrumental in enabling the launch of entirely new research programs, while some provide invaluable independent program reviews. The [National Academies Press](/National_Academies_Press) (NAP) serves as the official publisher for the [National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine), making its vast catalogue of publications readily available for free online reading. Furthermore, the full PDF versions of these books have been offered for free download since 2011, ensuring broad accessibility to their findings.

Beyond their written reports, the [National Academies](/National_academy) also fulfill a crucial public service by providing credentialed witnesses who are called upon to speak before various government bodies on issues of national importance. For instance, a committee chair might be asked to testify before a Senate Subcommittee on Primary Health and Retirement Security, part of the Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions, discussing critical topics such as rising mortality rates among working-age adults in the [US](/United_States_of_America). [31](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-31)

### Reports

#### Climate change

In 2001, the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council) (NRC) published a seminal report titled *Climate Change Science: An Analysis of Some Key Questions*. This publication underscored a critical reality: that national policy decisions, whether enacted in the immediate future or further down the line, would inexorably determine the extent of damage ultimately suffered by vulnerable human populations and ecosystems later in the 21st century. The report notably endorsed the findings put forth by the [Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change](/Intergovernmental_Panel_on_Climate_Change) (IPCC), explicitly stating that these findings accurately represented the views of the broader scientific community at the time:

> The changes observed over the last several decades are likely mostly due to human activities, but we cannot rule out that some significant part of these changes is also a reflection of natural variability. [Human-induced warming](/Anthropogenic_global_warming) and associated [sea level rise](/Sea_level_rise) are expected to continue through the 21st century ... The IPCC's conclusion that most of the observed warming of the last 50 years is likely to have been due to the increase in [greenhouse gas](/Greenhouse_gas) concentrations accurately reflects the current [2001] thinking of the scientific community on this issue. [32](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-32)

*It's almost as if the scientific community has been saying the same thing for decades, and yet... here we are. Some advice is simply too inconvenient to be truly heard.*

Years later, in 2013, the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council) followed up with another significant publication, the report *Abrupt Impacts of Climate Change: Anticipating Surprises*. This study offered a crucial updated perspective on the complex issue of [abrupt climate change](/Abrupt_climate_change) and its potentially far-reaching consequences. What distinguished this particular study from previous examinations of abrupt environmental shifts was its focused emphasis not only on abrupt climate changes themselves but also on the sudden, profound climate impacts that possess the capacity to severely disrupt the physical climate system, natural ecosystems, or human societies, often affecting multiple, interconnected areas of concern simultaneously. [33](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-33)

#### Sexual assault

In 2013, the [National Research Council](/National_Research_Council) released a sobering report titled *Estimating the Incidence of Rape and Sexual Assault*. [34](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-34) This critical document highlighted a deeply troubling statistic: approximately 80 percent of [sexual assaults](/Sexual_assault) tragically go unreported to law enforcement agencies. In response to this stark reality, the report put forth a series of recommendations, urging the [National Crime Victimization Survey](/National_Crime_Victimization_Survey) to adopt novel approaches to the interviewing of rape victims, including a crucial re-evaluation and modification of the wording used in interview questions to better capture the full scope of experiences.

In an article discussing the findings of this impactful report, Amber Stevenson, a clinical supervisor and therapist at the Nashville Sexual Assault Center, articulated a profound insight. She stated that [victim-blaming](/Victim_blaming) stood out as the principal barrier preventing victims from coming forward and reporting these heinous crimes:

> As long as we as a community continue to make victim-blaming statements, such as, "She put herself in this situation,"..."She didn't fight back, she must have wanted it," we will continue to see rapes go unreported ... We have to stop blaming the victim. The conversation needs to shift to the person who chose to rape. [35](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-35)

*A truth so obvious, yet so consistently ignored by those who prefer comfortable fictions. The problem isn't the victim; it's the lack of accountability and the twisted logic of a society that blames the injured for their wounds.*

#### Integrity in research

The 1992 report, *Responsible Science: Ensuring the Integrity of the Research Process*, served as a foundational document on the ethics and conduct of scientific inquiry. This critical work was subsequently updated and expanded in 2017 by the report, *Fostering Integrity in Research*. The necessity for this update was clearly articulated within the newer report:

> ... as experience has accumulated with various forms of research misconduct, detrimental research practices, and other forms of misconduct, as subsequent empirical research has revealed more about the nature of scientific misconduct, and because technological and social changes have altered the environment in which science is conducted, it is clear that the framework established more than two decades ago needs to be updated. [36](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-36)

One of the primary concerns meticulously addressed in the updated report is the alarming trend of a growing percentage of recently published research proving to be irreproducible. This troubling issue is attributed, in part, to inadequate support for robust standards of transparency across many scientific fields, as well as to the proliferation of various other detrimental research practices that undermine the reliability of scientific findings. [37](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-37) *Integrity, like so many virtues, seems to be something that constantly needs "fostering" and "updating." One might almost think it's not a natural state.*

### Other programs

Beyond its core advisory and report-generating functions, the [National Academies](/National_academy) also sponsor several other important initiatives. One such program is the Christine Mirzayan Science and Technology Policy Fellowship, an annual program designed for recent graduate students. This fellowship offers a unique opportunity for participants to spend three months immersed in the work of the [National Academies](/National_academy), gaining invaluable experience in the intersection of science, technology, and policy. [38](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-38) Additionally, the Academies previously administered the [Marian Koshland Science Museum](/Marian_Koshland_Science_Museum), located in downtown [Washington](/Washington,_D.C.), until its closure in 2017. The museum's mission was to engage the public with science. Since its closure, the museum has been superseded by LabX, an innovative program that leverages online resources and organizes nationwide public events. LabX's overarching aim is to enhance public awareness and understanding of scientific and evidence-based solutions to pressing community problems. [39](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-39)

### Revenue

It is a common misconception that the [National Academies](/National_academy) receive direct appropriations from the [federal government](/Federal_government_of_the_United_States). In reality, their operational revenue is generated primarily through grants and contracts secured from various federal agencies, supplemented by contributions from private sources. [40](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-40) [41](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-41) According to a 2023 report in *The [New York Times](/New_York_Times)*, while "about 70 percent of the National Academies budget comes from federal funds," the organization also actively raised private donations. These private contributions came from a diverse array of individuals, nonprofit organizations, and prominent companies, including [Chevron](/Chevron_Corporation), [Google](/Google), [Merck](/Merck_%26_Co.), and [Medtronic](/Medtronic). [42](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-42)

A particularly notable instance of private funding, which drew considerable scrutiny, involved the institution's role in advising the government on opioid policy. During this period, the [National Academies](/National_academy) received a substantial sum of $19 million from the [Sackler family](/Sackler_family) (who controlled [Purdue Pharma](/Purdue_Pharma)) between the years 2000 and 2021. [43](/National_Academies_of_Sciences,_Engineering,_and_Medicine#cite_note-43) *One might wonder how "independent, objective advice" remains untainted when such significant sums flow from entities with a vested interest in the very policies being advised upon. But I'm sure it's all perfectly above board.*

